@Node "Introduction" "phMask.guide/Introduction"
@Next "Requirements"
@Prev "Main"

@{b}@{u}Introduction@{ub}@{uu}

phMask is a hook module for ImageFX that can encode and decode
FL/CP/MEKO/Q0 masks. These masks can/are applied to images to hide
portions of them from view.

For the latest version and information, check the home page at
http://mafeking.scouts.org.au/~paulh/

@EndNode

@Node "Requirements" "phMask.guide/Requirements"
@Next "Installation"
@Prev "Introduction"

@{b}@{u}Requirements@{ub}@{uu}

phMask requires at @{b}minimum@{ub} the following to run:

   À ImageFX 2.6

   À 68020

@EndNode

@Node "Installation" "phMask.guide/Installation"
@Next "Usage"
@Prev "Requirements"

@{b}@{u}Installation@{ub}@{uu}

Versions of phMask are provided for the 68020 and 68030 CPUs. Simply copy
the version for your CPU into the ImageFX hooks directory.

@EndNode

@Node "Usage" "phMask.guide/Usage"
@Prev "Installation"
@Next "Acknowledgements"

@{b}@{u}Usage@{ub}@{uu}

@{b}To encode/decode a masked image@{ub}

   À Load the image to decode.

   À If the entire image is masked, set the region tool to full, otherwise
     set it to box and draw a rectangle that encloses the entire masked
     region (if you are decoding ensure it is exactly the masked region
     only and not any other outlying pixels otherwise the masking procedure
     WILL NOT WORK).

   À Select the hook @{b}phMask@{ub}.

   À Choose the type of mask you wish to use. If you are decoding a CP
     mask, you can click detect to attempt to retreive the code from the
     image file (this is not always possible or successful). Without the
     code, you cannot decode CP masks. If you do not supply a code, "CODE"
     will be used.

   À Except for the MEKO masks, the other masks complement themselves (ie
     if you run them again, the image will appear/disappear). To apply a
     MEKO mask, use MEKO+. To remove a MEKO mask, use MEKO-.

   À Select @{b}Okay@{ub}.

   À Hey presto, the image appears (or disappears into apparent garbage).

@EndNode

